## SECTION 9 — WRITING INSTRUCTIONS

> **POST GEN INSTRUCTION:** Follow these rules for every paragraph of body copy — no exceptions.

1. This is conversion copy — every sentence moves the buyer toward a purchase decision
2. Lead with buyer benefit, not product specs — specs support the benefit, never lead with them
3. Use buyer phrases from Section 5 naturally — "rich pigmentation," "salon-quality at home," "doesn't chip for weeks," "perfect for date night"
4. Primary keyword `MelodySusie valentines day nail products` in `<strong>` tags every mention — total 17 mentions for 1,400 words
5. Address buying objections directly — do not hedge or avoid them
6. Honest cons build trust — include them, then explain why the product is still the right buy
7. Discount codes placed near CTAs — mention naturally, not as a standalone paragraph
8. No editorial literary hooks — open sections with the buyer benefit or buying question directly
9. H2 sections are short and direct — buyers scan, they don't read long intros
10. Conclusion = final decision driver, not a summary
11. Internal links placed mid-post AFTER first product CTA only — anchor text natural, never forced
12. No related articles section in body — handled by site component
13. Language: **American English** — not British English
14. No banned AI patterns: no "elevate," "seamlessly," "game-changing," "dive into," "transformative"
15. No long em dashes — use comma or restructure
16. Sentence rhythm varies — short punchy sentences for key selling points, longer for context
17. No "we tested" language — write informed editorial observations from specs and confirmed review data
18. Valentine's Day is abbreviated "Valentine's Day" throughout — not "V-Day" in body copy (only acceptable in casual aside if needed)
19. GEO terms woven naturally near CTAs — "ships to the USA," "free US shipping on orders over $129.99," "order early for Valentine's Day delivery"
20. Intro must not open with: "Valentine's Day is a time for love" or any calendar/occasion preamble — open with the buyer's decision or the nail look goal
